<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18771022-783">
               <interp inst="t18771022-783" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18771022"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18771022-783" type="date" value="18771022"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18771022-783-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-783-18771022 t18771022-783-offence-1 t18771022-783-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>783. <persName id="def1-783-18771022" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-783-18771022" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-783-18771022" type="surname" value="BOULTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-783-18771022" type="given" value="ARTHUR EDWARD FREDERICK"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">ARTHUR EDWARD FREDERICK BOULTON</hi>, Feloniously</persName>
                  <rs id="t18771022-783-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18771022-783-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="breakingPeace"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18771022-783-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="wounding"></interp> attempting to discharge a loaded pistol at <persName id="t18771022-name-215" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-215" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-215" type="surname" value="LEVY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-215" type="given" value="SOLOMON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-215" type="occupation" value="wholesale clothier"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18771022-783-offence-1 t18771022-name-215"></join>Solomon Levy</persName> with intent to do—him grievous bodily harm.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. MILLWOOD</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-216" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-216" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-216" type="surname" value="LEVY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-216" type="given" value="SOLOMON"></interp>SOLOMON LEVY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a wholesale clothier, of 38, Upper East Smith-field—on 18th October, about 3 p.m., I was in the billiard-room of the "Woolpack, Minories—the prisoner came in, made a remark upon the manner in which some one made a stroke, and then he said that he would play any one for a half-sovereign or a sovereign—Mr. Arnett answered him in a joking kind of way "All right, I will play you!"—after the game which was being played was over, the prisoner took up a cue and attempted to strike a ball, and Mr. Arnett and the prisoner appeared about to commence—they both made two or three ineffectual strokes, knocking the balls about, and the marker said "I will have none of this nonsense, there are gentlemen waiting to play," and took the cue out of the prisoner's hands—the prisoner then walked across the room to a young man on the opposite side, saying "I will have my half-sovereign I have staked"—to my perfect knowledge, he had never drawn any money out; in fact, the marker said that he would not have any gambling—I am positive he never staked any money—several persons said at once "You never staked any money!"—he then attempted to strike the young man—the marker got between them and said "You shall not fight!"—he attempted to catch the marker by the throat, but he was too quick for him, and caught him by his throat with one hand and by his wrist with the other, and pushed him towards the door—I opened the door, and the marker put him out, and told some one to ring the bell—the potman came up, and the prisoner was put downstairs—hearing that he was making a disturbance downstairs, I saw him outside on the pavement, and some coppers rolling about which were handed to him, he picked some up himself, and from a stooping position he turned towards the door, looked round deliberately at everybody standing there, drew a pistol from behind him, and presented it at my head—I was about two feet from him—I had never spoken to him—I ducked my head to avoid the shot, and the <hi rend="italic">next</hi> thing I saw was that Mr. Brown had collared him on one side by the right wrist, and Detective Hutt on the other—the pistol was in his right hand—on the way to the station I saw blood on Mr. Brown's hand, and at the station I saw the inspector draw seven charges from the pistol—the prisoner said to me "I am sorry I did not shoot you, you son of a bitch,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187710220051"></xptr>
               <p>I will give it you when I come out"—he said that over and over again, and he said to the detective "I will give it to you too"—no doubt he had been drinking a little, but he appeared sober.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by the Prisoner.</hi> I could not see whether the revolver was on full cock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-217" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-217" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-217" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-217" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD BROWN</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at 3, Devonport Street, Commercial Road, and am a stevedore—on 18th October I was playing at billiards with Mr. Arnett, and saw the prisoner come in—he wanted to play Mr. Arnett for half a sovereign, but Mr. Arnett would not—the prisoner took up a cue and said "This is the way to hit the balls!"—Mr. Arnett took a cue and did not hit the balls—the marker said "I cannot have this nonsense," and took the cue away—the prisoner went up to a young man and said "I demand my half-sovereign I deposited with you"—he said "You deposited no half-sovereign"—the prisoner got into a fighting attitude—the marker got between them, and the prisoner was put out—I was after<lb></lb>wards told that he had a pistol in his possession—I went down, saw a little scuffle in the passage, and the prisoner was shoved out on to the pavement—he got up, put his right hand behind him, and drew a revolver and pointed it at Mr. Levy—I caught him by the hand, and took hold of the revolver, and the nipple came down on my hand; here is the wound it made, so that it must have been at full cock—he was given in custody—I had not seen him give any money to any one.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> I said before the Lord Mayor "There was a tussle, and the hammer came down"—there was little tussle in getting it away—I do not think I could have cocked it in that way—you had a pistol pocket, made for the purpose of carrying a revolver.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-218" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-218" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-218" type="surname" value="COOPER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-218" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM COOPER</persName>
                  </hi>. I rent the billiard-room at the Woolpack—on 18th December the prisoner came in about 3 o'clock—four gentlemen were playing at billiards, and he challenged the worst player of the four to play for a half-sovereign, but playing for money is not allowed—he went down and came up with his coat <hi rend="italic">off</hi>, and began knocking the balls about—I picked up the balls as he was talking a lot of nonsense, and said "This won't suit me; you had better go somewhere else and play"—he said to a gentleman there "I will take my stake money"—he said "What do you mean?" and the prisoner squared up at him—I went between them—he tried to seize me by the throat, but I was too quick for him, and seized him—I asked a gentleman to ring for the potman, who came up, and I said "Show that gentleman outside"—I did not see the prisoner produce any money.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-219" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-219" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-219" type="surname" value="BLACKMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-219" type="given" value="ALFRED"></interp>ALFRED BLACKMAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am potman and waiter at the Woolpack—I went upstairs when the bell rang, and they had got the prisoner outside the door—he asked me the marker's name—I said "I will tell you downstairs"—he went down and asked for the <hi rend="italic">bos</hi>, meaning the landlord—I said "He is upstairs lying down"—he placed his left hand on my shoulder and his right behind him, pulled out a revolver, and said "My dear boy, I have got a small instrument here which I mean doing some mischief with to those upstairs if I do not get my half-sovereign"—I told him if he had been done out of a half-sovereign I would send for the landlord, and he would go up and try to rectify it, but he laughed at me and would not take any notice—he then said he wanted to see the God d—<hi rend="italic">bos</hi>, and if he did not see the <hi rend="italic">bos</hi> in less than two minutes he would force his way into the billiard-room—I said "It is 100 to 1 that you don't"—he tried</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187710220052"></xptr>
               <p>to go to the staircase, and I called out "John, you go upstairs, you know the gentlemen better than I do; you ask which of them has go this half-sovereign"—two gentlemen then came out of the billiard-room downstairs—the prisoner said that he would not go out until he saw the <hi rend="italic">bos</hi>—he was pushed out on to the pavement, and fell on his back, and some coppers fell out of his jacket-pocket—he picked some up, and some people picked up the others and gave them to him—he put them in his pocket, put his hand behind him, and drew out a revolver—I sang out "Here comes the revolver"—he presented it at Mr. Levy's head, and Brown reached over my shoulder and seized his wrist, and took it away—he showed it to me three times inside the house—it was not cocked—the fourth time was outside.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-220" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-220" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-220" type="surname" value="HUTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-220" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM HUTT</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">City Detective</hi>). On 18th October I went to this billiard-room to see a gentleman—I saw the prisoner take a cue up and attempt to strike a ball—the marker saw that the other gentleman did not intend to play, and took the cue out of the prisoner's hand, and said "I will have no nonsense"—the prisoner walked up to a young man, and said "Where is my half sovereign?"—the young man seemed frightened, and said "I have no money of yours"—the marker stepped between them, grasped him by the throat, and he was taken downstairs—afterwards they said that he had a revolver, and I went down behind Mr. Brown—he attempted to stop Mr. Collins, who pushed him out on the pavement—some coppers fell out of his pocket which were picked up—I heard Black<lb></lb>man say "He has got a revolver"—Brown and the potman seized him, and Brown took the revolver from his hand—I seized his right hand, twisted him round, and said "I am a police officer; I shall take you in custody"—he said "D——you, I will shoot you"—I said "I will bet you don't"—I did not see whether the revolver was cocked or not—the charge was drawn at the station—there were seven chambers loaded with bullets—he said that he was very sorry he had not settled some of us, and he would do it, and that he would shoot me—he was perfectly sober, but no doubt he had been drinking.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-221" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-221" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-221" type="surname" value="EGAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-221" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN EGAN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Police Inspector</hi>). The prisoner was brought to Seething Lane station—I read the charge to him, and he said "I wish I had shot somebody"—I drew the charges; these are the bullets (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>).</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">The prisoner in his Defence stated that he had just landed from the United States, where he was in the habit of carrying a pistol, and thought it safer to keep it in his pocket than to leave it on a table, and having taken two or three glasses of stout, which he was not accustomed to, he did not know what occurred, and that the pistol must have got cocked in the struggle.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18771022-783-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
